For fucks sake, you can find a job somewhere instead of sitting on your ass all goddamn day, if you try.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not sure what you're trying to say.  I wasn't implying that people should be collecting benefits if they aren't citizens.  My point was simply that we don't need to worry about illegals collecting welfare because they can't.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>This is true to an extent, I suppose as is everything... When the market is flooded with low skill level workers, wages drop all around. Companies can gather enough workers to work 10-20 hours per week and then do not have to pay for things like health insurance. This is great for the company, but what about Tom, Dick and Harry who work 4-5 of these jobs to make ends meet? It's really fucking the people at this skill level right in the ass and the businesses taking advantage of it are cackling as they roll in the dough. (you'd never guess I'm a democrat and Amm is a republican eh?)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You're oversimplifying this.  If you increase supply of labor, and demand is constant, wages will decrease.  This is true and is the basic idea you are suggesting here.  However, this is why it doesn't work.  Adding more people into the labor force has a 2 fold effect.  It increases both supply and demand, and the 2 forces cancel each other out with respect to wage changes, leaving wages constant in the end.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Uncontrolled immigration is NOT a good thing overall for current US citizens. We have plenty of dumb fucks wandering the streets that could fill these positions already, no need to import more.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm not saying we should have completely uncontrolled immigration.  I think we need to be somewhat selective about whom we let in.  We need to be especially careful not to let in people who are a security risk to our government.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Another thing People say if you send US jobs overseas that it will lower the cost of merchandise which will help us out. No one realizes if we kept all of our jobs here we would be making MORE money and have more JOBS as a whole, and would be able to spend more money on any particular item we wanted.<br>
<br>
1) You make minimum wage but apples cost 2 dollars a pound<br>
2) You make 15 dollars an hour but apples cost 3 dollars a pound<br>
<br>
I'll take #2<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If we stopped sending jobs overseas, it isn't going to raise your wages from 5 to 15 bucks an hour.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Ammelen's take on the world:<br>
<br>
money &gt; people<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, I just don't believe in artificially propping up wages to levels that are inappropriate for the work being done.  The value of labor is determined by what you contribute, what you produce in total, not how much time you put into it.  This is why minimum wage is silly.  If you sit around all day and make one widget at a factory that profits a company 3 cents, but you take 16 hours to do it, minimum wage is silly.  Minimum wage prevents us from having certain products and services available because it simply makes some lines of business unprofitable.  Companies should be able to pay whatever they want, and if people decide that the wages are too low, they can go work somewhere else.  If the wages are appropriate to what people can contribute though, i.e. their productivity, then they won't get more elsewhere.  If the wages are too low for the employees level of productivity, then they will get more elsewhere and they will take that option.<br>
<br>
As long as no one is forcing you to take a job, and it's entirely your choice whether you wish to take it, a company should be able to offer you anything they want to offer you.<br>
<br>
