<br>
Personally, if I had my choice, I'd focus more on deficit reduction.  I would happily pass on tax cuts in the short term if ALL of the money went to deficit reduction and NONE of it went to more porkbarrel spending.  Sadly, I don't trust the government to have the restraint to do this.  In the long run, tax cuts are not real unless they are accompanied by spending cuts.  A tax cut which creates a deficit just defers the tax to a later date.  One of the problems though is that as soon as the democrats see a surplus, they want to spend it all and create more government programs that we'll get locked into and be unable to cancel later on.  At least by returning the money to the people it helps to encourage fiscal responsibility.<br>
<br>
The reasons for the tax cut do make some sense.  Our economy needs some stimulus, and it's well known that tax cuts stimulate the economy.  Just look at what Reagan did.  His tax cut took us from the horribly economic recession of the Carter years to an unprecedented 20 year economic expansion.  Bush believes (maybe he's right, we'll have to wait and see) that the reductions in taxes will put our economy back on track.<br>
<br>
Ideally, I think we should have alternating periods of deficit and surplus, but they should roughly balance each other out.  In times of recession, people make less money, and the tax base goes down, so it is inevitable that government revenue go down too, and a deficit occurs.  In times of economic prosperity, like the most of Clinton's term, people make more money.  The tax base goes up and we should have a surplus.<br>
<br>
