<br>
No, I don't want anyone to lose his job.  However, the company is not responsible for taking care of you or anyone else.  Employment in the United States is &quot;at will,&quot; meaning that companies can terminate employment at any time for any reason (other than a few reasons covered under anti-discrimination laws).  The company only owes you compensation for the amount of time you have worked.  Sure, it sucks that someone can lose his job.  However, the company's job is to make money for its stockholders, not to care for its employees until they retire.  They offer the employees money in exchange for labor.  The employees will quit the job and go to another if they have an offer for more money, the company will fire the employees if they can get the labor cheaper.  This is the basis of capitalism and ensures that labor and goods are sold at fair market values.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'm saying when the government royally screws it's own like that they should be willing to help out some.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
